<Base title="A Man Eating His Own Tail — Michalina Sablik">
  <div class="container page-content">
    <h1>A Man Eating His Own Tail</h1>
    <p class="exhibition-detail-venue">CasCaDas ArtSpace, Barcelona | 2024</p>
    <div class="exhibition-detail-body">
      <p>The installation references the mythological Ouroboros—a serpent consuming itself. Historically associated with solar cults, this symbol represents infinity, eternal return, and cyclical time. The creature embodies matter's eternity and the reconciliation of opposites, though it can also signify foolishness or circular behavior.</p>
      <p>The artist explores non-linear temporal thinking found in indigenous and pre-Enlightenment epistemologies. Philosopher Timothy Morton's work informs this approach, advocating for complexity and ambiguity over linear rationality. Branas works with found materials from botanical gardens, allotments, beaches, and markets in Barcelona's El Raval district. He fashions comets from supermarket brochures, masks from fruit peels, and archetypal figures from plants and sticks.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="exhibition-detail-credits">
      <p><strong>Dates:</strong> September 26 – November 2, 2024</p>
      <p><strong>Artist:</strong> Przemek Branas</p>
      <p><strong>Curator:</strong> Michalina Sablik</p>
      <p><strong>Partners:</strong> CasCaDas ArtSpace, Adam Mickiewicz Institute, Krupa Art Foundation</p>
      <p><strong>Documentation:</strong> Eva Carasol</p>
    </div>
